        },
        {
            "text": "resilience can be defined as the system’s ability to maintain its integrity and its performance, at least partially, while under internal or external variations and disturbances (i.e. pressures, constraints, failures, errors, violations, hazards), whether nominal, extreme, or exceptional.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.95
        },
        {
            "text": "defined as a company’s ability to respond effectively to environmental disruptions and transform itself to emerge stronger from a challenging situation.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.95
        },
        {
            "text": "we develop a trajectory model of organizational resilience that focuses on how actors project temporal trajectories of responses toward disruptive events, reconstitute the trajectories in immediate response to the event, and reconfigure the trajectories toward the ensuing future.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.92
        },
        {
            "text": "the concept of resilience draws attention to systems as well as individuals, to partial maintenance of integrity and performance, to the opposite of brittleness, and to disturbances that vary both in scale and source.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.9
        },
        {
            "text": "resilience is a multifaceted concept that reflects businesses’ ability to foresee, confront, and benefit from sudden disruptive change to survive, grow, and flourish.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.9
        },
        {
            "text": "this lens focuses on the processes through which actors maintain a sense of coherence between present, past, and future in the face of disruptive events.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.88
        },
        {
            "text": "this study objective is to theoretically discuss and empirically investigate the extent to which the interplay between the domains of knowledge complexity (managerial, strategic, and operational) facilitates firm performance and the role of organizational resilience in this relationship.",
            "is_formal": true,
            "score": 0.85
        },
        {
